{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a41dcf6e-d8cc-40e9-873a-332473a7a02a","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general knowledge:\n\n## Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship with `createdump`. On macOS, use the OS-level mechanisms instead:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Check for Apple crash reports** — macOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n3. **Use `lldb` to generate a core file** (if you can reproduce):\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp\n   (lldb) run\n   # after crash:\n   (lldb) process save-core /tmp/myapp.core\n   ```\n\n4. **Configure `/cores/` directory** — macOS can write core dumps to `/cores/` if:\n   ```bash\n   sudo mkdir -p /cores\n   sudo chmod 1777 /cores\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Look for `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp --core /cores/core.12345\n   ```\n\n**Key note:** Apple's System Integrity Protection (SIP) may prevent core dumps for signed/entitled binaries. You may need to codesign with `get-task-allow` entitlement or disable SIP in development.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5d1fd09d-e30b-4c8e-8120-f23525b3ccea","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"6811:2EE789:C40D4A:D1B080:6A0B00F5"},"id":"75ee77bd-a7fb-4f8b-9614-dd13062804f1","timestamp":"2026-05-18T12:07:33.425Z","parentId":"52d55808-ecbf-4f86-9ee2-9f0531bd3451"}
